rComments: Awesome professor. Knows her material. Informative class.
She's a great prof. with a sense of humor. Attend class, read her slides and understand them and you'll succeed very well.

I tell all my friends to take this class. The Prof is very knowledgeable and engaging. Because of this course I am now looking for graduate school that specializes in that region. The only thing I didn't like were the pop quizzes!

Had her in my third semester at Uottawa, and this prof is by far one of my worst. Was looking to register for further courses for next year, and seeing her available made me shiver so I decided to write this. She showed up late to class multiple times, often unprepared, and seemed to have a minimal grasp on the course content. AVOID at all costs!:)

One of the best courses taught at UOttawa. I'm now doing my Masters at UoT on Middle East politics because of this class. Prof. Al-Fattal is very knowledgeable about the region and gives lots of relevant examples. Be ready to read though.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Amazing lectures ', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: Why is she even a prof. Worst prof ever, she has no idea how to incorporate material SHE TAUGHT into exams. And how the hell are you going to make a 12 page paper worth 10%.  Never again.
The slides are very helpful and the class will help you understand what's going on in the world. I started another class and find myself  going back to her slides as a refresher.

She's a good professor but I'm not going to lie her class gets a little boring. She's definitely knowledgeable and very nice but she lacks dynamism, the good thing is as long as you read the slides on blackboard and read the textbook you don't really need to attend class. She grades your papers farely and she is accessible.
I'm an exchange students and I enjoyed the open discussion in class, I wish we had that in Europe. I'm very glad I took this course.

I really liked the prof. she was cool and down to earth. The exams were what I had expected. The research proposal was a challenge since it's my 1st time writing one, but the TAs were helpful all the way!

Wasn't an easy course but you can still do well if you do hw on time and go to class. Attendance is not mandatory but you learn a lot and she practically tells you what will be on the exam. The research paper was challenging, but the exams are relatively easy and straight from the notes.
I really liked this class. Prof. was helpful when asked questions. She is obviously passionate about what she does.

Amazing class, the student who are complaining are ridiculous! She repeated several times that "this is a big class so please hand your work on time". She was very caring and patient answering questions and giving review sessions before exams. Those who studied did well in her class.
If you are willing to work hard for this course you can learn a lot and get a good grade. The key is to attend lectures and ask questions.
I really enjoyed this course.
Wouldn't take a class again with this prof
Very insightful lectures, but she expects you to work for your mark.
I have never met a prof. who reached out to her student to help them succeed as much as she did. The final review was very helpful. Amazing lectures, I learned so much about international relations.
Awful

In class it feels like she's seeing the course material for the first time and trying to string a lecture together. Confuses basic concepts and reads off the slides. Makes rude unwarranted comments degrading our ability to pay attention in class and to do well on upcoming assignments. Did not show up for her office hours after I waited 30 minutes.
Shows little regard for her students. Lectures are mundane and uninspiring.
Prof. Alfattal is a very kind and smart person. She gives amazing lectures that helped me understand international relations. You should attend all lectures if you want to do well.
Excellent

Very supportive professor. She helped me through difficult time which made this class manageable. Those leaving rude comments about her teaching obviously haven't been to class. I feel more prepared now for my 3rd/4th year.

Professor Al-Fattal genuinely cares about her students and wants them to succeed. She is clear about her expectations on assignments, as well as the midterm and final exams. The best way to do well in her class is to attend lectures, ask questions, and be informed about relevant current events, especially those linked to International Relations.

I really enjoyed the class and the open topic research paper was a great opportunity to develop interest in the course material and apply it to a topic I was interested in in the real world context.  Textbook was not necessary but the reader was. Participation matters, she will remember while she's grading. the lectures were always  had real world
Truly one of the nicest profs I had so far. Although some of the material can be dry you can do well if you go to class, do the reading and speak to the prof.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Accessible outside class', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: One of the best teachers in my 2 yrs at the university. She presented the material clearly, and spent a lot of time after class answering our questions. But you have to work for your A.

An average workload of a 2nd year POL course. She was a good teacher, the marking was pretty fair if you knew the main concepts. I didn't get why she was so strict about late assignments, when she was almost always late for class herself. She also could have been a bit clearer in what she wanted in the main paper, but overall it was decent.

Prof Al-Fattal is very knowledgable but her lectures are pretty dry. Its not necessary to go to class, her lecture notes contain all the important stuff.  The 15 page final paper is a little excessive. Grading criteria for midterm is unclear.

I can't stress enough how awesome this class was, makes waking up early in the morning worth it! The lecture style was very engaging and she respected student's input! Those who are saying tough grader, it's ridiculous, if you study you will do just fine.

This prof expected a lot from second year students. She does not accept broken bones as an excuse for late assignments. At the end of the semester, she sent an email only to the students who finished with the highest grades saying "Now that you have received your marks I'd appreciate if you could leave your valuable feedback online at RateMyProf"
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Graded by few things', 'Tough grader']

rComments: Insightful prof. and interesting lectures, you will learn a lot. Gives lots of examples to clarify the material. Highly recommended. Don't pay attention to the negative comments, probably written by students who didn't study and didn't do well.

Prof. Al-Fattal is a good lecturer who always tries her best to ensure that students understand the material. She is very receptive to feedback, and is willing to integrate different learning styles into her class. She is friendly and approachable, and her criteria can be confusing, but she is always willing to clarify. Don't hand things in late!

She cared about her students and wanted them to do well. However, she read off the slides quite a bit and sometimes contradicted herself. I found the marking fair. You can get a good mark if you put in the work.

Very rude and unwilling to help! She doesn't know most of the material off the top of her own head but will find a way to make you feel stupid for not remembering something. Reads off slides she copy/pastes from wikipedia. The research proposal was horrible, she gave a 4 page outline that somehow managed to make it even more confusing.

What should I say about the wonderful Rouba, not much. One of the worst teachers I have had since my 2 yrs, doesnt care for her students. AKA straight up insults and blames them left and right for things that she wasnt doing! She was never clear on what we needed to do and made me laugh at least once a class on something stupid or wrong she said.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Tough grader', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Very upset by this professor who is obviously an educated and kind woman but she really fell short in teaching this class.

I have amazing grades in all my classes (for once) and hers is the only class I'm struggling to pass. She is horrible I have never met a teacher so demeaning. She makes her students feel worthless and does not know how to explain her lectures. Her final review was giving exam questions which turned out to be completely different than the exam.
Hate her

At first I thought I was really going to like this professor but after a few classes it was very clear that she was not familiar with what she was trying to teach us. She gave very vague instructions for our research proposal but expected us to have already known how to do one. Was quite rude when it came to final review.

Had a 15 page research proposal to write and she was not clear whatsoever of what she wanted. Asked for a doctor's note when i didn't attend one class although attendance is not mandatory. She does not know the course content and is unable to properly answer students when asked a specific question

I'm going to start off by saying I missed her class and she questioned my whereabouts even though her class has no mandatory attendance. She gave a 15 page proposal with such horrible explanation. She has the worst teaching methods and kept comparing everything to the middle easte when it had nothing to do with it. Avoid at all costs.

Rudest professor I have ever had. She flat out told the class she doesn't read the exam just skims for key words. She was asked about feminism and said I don't remember it since I'm not writing the exam. Her TA was horrible and her class was extremely boring and very unclear.

If you're looking for a professor who cares, look elsewhere.  Dry material you've probably already learned a million times, so if you don't need this class, avoid it.  Pretty heavy workload, with a few papers, one being a 15 page research proposal.  Overall, I wouldn't take a class with her again if I don't have to, didn't enjoy her class at all.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: While she appears to be a very nice lady she is a horrible professor. She consistently read off her slides class after class. She kept on repeating how overwhelmingly big our class was. Newsflash - this is a university lecture, accept it. She arrived late multiple times and always seemed ill prepared. The course is difficult. At least she is nice

Highly boring prof who read directly off the slides every class. Showed up late a number of times, as well as unprepared several times and seemed to not have a full grasp on the class. Wouldn't take this class unless there are no other options. At the end of  the day its not insanely difficult, it just makes you fall asleep every classsszzzzzz.
Very unclear in explaining reviews, and her expectations for assignments. Admitted that she doesn't actually read students' exam answers, just looks for a few key words.

She reads off the slides, which made going to an 8:30am class really feel pointless. Her grading criteria is super unclear and her answers to questions are unclear as well. Would not recommend her to anyone taking this particular class.
She is nice, very smart and passionate; however, she is very hard and unclear of her expectations.
Such a horrible professor. Gave a 12-15 page paper with 4 pages of explanations and the assignment still made no sense. Non sympathetic with her students what so ever.

The only benefit about this prof is I liked her accent. She seems very nice when she's teaching, and she does teach quite well. Then you go to her office hours and she turns into Lucifer, removing marks if you challenge your grade. She also told me she had no sympathy for me. Super rude prof, avoid her. Some of her TAS mark hard, others don't.

Professor Rouba is inspirational. I see all the messages about how hard her ccourse is but what is everyone expecting ? One shall remember that only hard work justifies and legitimizes relevant knowledge assimilation. I would take her class any day. All those difficult concepts she explained to us in class now helps me today. Proof. Take her.

Avoid at all costs!  To be fair, she really meant well and I think that she really wanted us to do well.  But now for the real problems... Rouba really didn't know what she was grading or how to teach. She would constantly bring Middle Eastern politics in, when they didn't apply. She also evaluated us using a France grading method (way harder).

With apologies to a clearly learned and caring professor, this class was a mess. Complex  material was highly distorted by the 'Student Presentation' format - where the bulk of class is made up of undergrads' PowerPoint projects. That said, if you want to pay for the privilege of watching undergrads argue about Israel and Islam, here's your chance.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: This class requires a lot of reading and the prof expects you to work for it. However, it is doable and the prof is willing to help if you do the work. Good class, I learned a lot from it!
Great professor and really knows her material. However, there is a heavy course load so be ready for a lot of readings and a lot of information to take in for evaluations and assignments.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Beware of pop quizzes', 'Participation matters']

rComments: Professor al-Fattal's teaching on the MENA region is very comprehensive - she covers from the pre-Islamic period to present day so be prepared for VERY long notes come exam time. That being said, because the content is so interesting, it is enjoyable to study. Only (minor) critique is to shorten student discussion time a little bit. Great course!

Prof Al-Fattal is very intelligent and holds a strong understanding of the material. You must attend class or you will not perform well. Make sure you arrange to meet with her if you do not understand a concept, she really wants to see her students succeed. Pay attention, and make sure to participate in class. She wants to help you learn, not fail.

Do not expect this class to be an Easy A, but if you put in the time and effort it can be! Professor Rouba is an amazing teacher, but she expects a lot from her students which is understandable in a third year level course! Put in the effort and make sure to keep up to date with current events and key historical figures and dates!

La professeure Rouba Al-Fattal est excellente, connaissante, clair et se soucie de ses élèves. Elle est très raisonnable, a des attentes claires. Les lectures sont importantes, il y a des quiz, il faut être attentif et rester à jour. Je recommande cette professeure, elle a beaucoup à vous apprendre.
Helpful understanding the Middle East -North Africa!
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Inspirational', 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: So kind and caring for students. She's extremely knowledgeable and gives fascinating and engaging lectures. One of the best professors I've ever had!

Great prof! She is extremely helpful, really cares about her student, and treats all equally. She strongly encourages student engagement in class debates. She also rewards students for their efforts and is a fair marker. Furthermore, she is extremely lenient, so long as students do not abuse that privilege.

Professor Al-Fattal truly cared about her students and went out of her way to help you, open to help after office hours and always answering emails, and was a fair marker. She is probably the most passionate teacher I've ever had getting the class involved in intriguing debates and sharing her enlivening expertise. Highly recommended.

She is also very helpful if you gave questions. The material is very interesting. Suggestions for prof is to improve on organizational skills ie: setting a time limits on presentations ie: 10 maximum so there's enough time for lectures.

Rouba Al-Fattal is a good prof, who is keen to help her students succeed. If you put in the effort and do the readings, you will do well. My only complaint is the level of "students teaching students" via class presentations on the readings. I prefer more lecturing because I want to hear what the prof (the expert) has to say. Overall, good class.
Very interesting class

The professor is nice and attentive. She cares about everyone's welfare and does not hesitate to give a hand. The class was mostly based on presentations. Very few lectures. Make sure to arrive on time in class.

This course was very eye-opening. The professor was engaging, courteous and attentive. The class was based mostly on presentations. There were very few lectures. Make sure to arrive on time in class as there might be quizzes that you could miss if  you are late.
Good teacher. class based mainly on student presentations and a few lecturing. very fair teacher.
